        <p>All plans are billed annually (figures above reflect annual billing). Month-to-month pricing is available at a higher rate.</p>

        <h2>The two sides of Houzz Pro</h2>

        <h3>Side 1: Business management platform</h3>
        <p>The project management tools in Houzz Pro cover what most remodeling contractors actually need day-to-day:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Estimates and proposals</strong> — Build line-item estimates with markup controls and send professional proposals clients can approve online</li>
          <li><strong>Project timelines</strong> — Milestone-based scheduling that clients can view; simpler than Buildertrend's Gantt but easier to learn</li>
          <li><strong>Client portal</strong> — Clients log in to see project status, documents, and selections</li>
          <li><strong>Selections management</strong> — Track material and finish choices with client approval</li>
          <li><strong>Invoicing and payments</strong> — Send invoices and collect payments including credit card (fees apply)</li>
          <li><strong>Change orders</strong> — Create and get client approval digitally</li>
          <li><strong>QuickBooks integration</strong> — Sync invoices and payments</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Side 2: Houzz marketplace and lead generation</h3>
        <p>This is where Houzz Pro differentiates itself from every other remodeling platform. Houzz has one of the largest design-inspiration communities on the internet — homeowners browse millions of photos, save ideas, and then find contractors to execute their vision.</p>

        <p>With a Houzz Pro subscription, your business gets:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Enhanced profile visibility in Houzz's contractor directory</li>
          <li>Access to leads from homeowners looking for contractors in your area</li>
          <li>Ability to respond to "Find Pros" requests</li>
          <li>Portfolio of your project photos visible to millions of monthly visitors</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>Does the lead generation actually work?</strong> Yes — but with caveats. In metro areas with strong design communities (LA, NYC, Chicago, Seattle, Boston, Miami), Houzz leads are real and can be significant. In smaller markets or rural areas, Houzz traffic is lower and lead quality varies. Before subscribing primarily for lead generation, check how many contractor profiles exist in your specific market on Houzz.com — more competition means fewer leads per contractor.</p>

        <h2>The design tools</h2>
        <p>Pro and Ultimate plans include design tools unique to Houzz: mood board creation, inspiration board sharing with clients, and 3D room visualization. For design-build remodelers who sell their design vision before the project starts, these tools have real value in the pre-sale phase.</p>

        <p>Clients can browse Houzz's photo library, mark favorites, and share those inspiration boards directly with you — creating a visual brief before any project meetings. This shortens the design discovery process significantly.</p>

        <h2>What Houzz Pro does well</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Price — $65–$149/mo is dramatically more accessible than Buildertrend</li>
          <li>Dual platform value (PM + lead generation + design tools)</li>
          <li>Clean, modern interface that clients find intuitive</li>
          <li>Design inspiration integration unique in the market</li>
          <li>Quick setup — most users are functional within a week</li>
          <li>Strong for client-facing communication and visual presentation</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Where Houzz Pro falls short</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Scheduling depth</strong> — No dependency-linked Gantt scheduling; milestone view only. For complex projects with 8+ trades, this is a real limitation.</li>
          <li><strong>Subcontractor management</strong> — No bid management, sub portals, or purchase orders. You'll manage subs outside the platform.</li>
          <li><strong>Job costing</strong> — Budget vs. actual tracking is less robust than Buildertrend or JobTread.</li>
          <li><strong>Commercial limitations</strong> — Houzz Pro is designed for residential remodeling and doesn't work for commercial projects.</li>
          <li><strong>Lead generation variability</strong> — Inconsistent results by market; smaller markets see fewer leads.</li>
          <li><strong>Integration ecosystem</strong> — Fewer third-party integrations than larger platforms.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Who Houzz Pro is for</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Kitchen, bath, and whole-home remodeling contractors</li>
          <li>Design-build firms where visual presentation is part of the sales process</li>
          <li>Contractors in metro areas where Houzz traffic drives real leads</li>
          <li>Small-to-mid operations ($150K–$1.5M/year) where Buildertrend's price isn't justified</li>
          <li>Firms that want a combined PM + marketing platform</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Who should look elsewhere</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>High-volume remodelers coordinating multiple subs — Buildertrend's scheduling depth is needed</li>
          <li>Contractors in smaller markets where Houzz lead generation won't deliver value</li>
          <li>Commercial contractors — Procore or Buildertrend are more appropriate</li>
          <li>Builders doing ground-up construction — Houzz Pro is remodeling-focused</li>
        </ul>

